million people are insecure.

11:28.521 --> 11:33.126 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: Economic and racial
divides are very much a focus in

11:33.159 --> 11:35.762 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the United States right now,
whether through the lens of

11:35.795 --> 11:40.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
criminal justice, education, or
income inequality. Today, a

11:40.300 --> 11:44.137 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
major new survey documents the
extent to which those divides

11:44.170 --> 11:48.107 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
also play a role in parenting,
and the choices and concerns

11:48.141 --> 11:52.111 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
mothers and fathers face. As an
example, the report released by

11:52.145 --> 11:56.449 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the Pew Research Center finds
that lower-income parents tend

11:56.482 --> 12:00.019 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to worry that their child might
be a victim of violence, or run

12:00.053 --> 12:03.289 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
into trouble with the police.
While higher-income parents are

12:03.323 --> 12:07.193 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
more likely to worry that their
children's overly busy schedules

12:07.226 --> 12:10.997 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
may be causing them stress. To
help us explore more of the

12:11.030 --> 12:14.334 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
report's findings, and the
potential effects different

12:14.367 --> 12:18.538 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
child-raising practices might
have, we turn to Kim Parker of

12:18.571 --> 12:22.475 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the Pew Research Center, and
Lawrence Aber, he's a professor

12:22.508 --> 12:27.280 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of psychology and public policy
at New York University. And we

12:27.313 --> 12:31.050 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
welcome you both. Kim Parker,
broadly speaking, to start this

12:31.084 --> 12:34.520 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
off, how much difference is
there in the parenting styles

12:34.554 --> 12:38.257 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and approaches of parents at the
lower end of the income scale

12:38.291 --> 12:41.761 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and at the upper-end? KIM
PARKER, PEW RESEARCH CENTER: I

12:41.794 --> 12:43.796 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
think the differences are less
in their style and approach, and

12:43.830 --> 12:45.798 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
more in their outlook and their
worries and concerns and their

12:45.832 --> 12:49.335 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
aspirations. We found that for
lower income parents, their

12:49.369 --> 12:52.839 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
financial instability can really
limit their children's access to

12:52.872 --> 12:56.676 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a safe environment and the kinds
of extracurricular and enriching

12:56.709 --> 12:59.812 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
activities that many more
affluent parents may take for

12:59.846 --> 13:02.749 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
granted. WOODRUFF: Well, for
example we saw, I think we have

13:02.782 --> 13:05.785 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a graphic to show this,
participating -- this is just

13:05.818 --> 13:07.987 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
participating in after school
activities. Families earning

13:08.021 --> 13:12.625 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
over $75,000 a year, 84 percent
of those children participate in

13:12.659 --> 13:16.295 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
organized sports, 62 percent in
some sort of organized music and

13:16.329 --> 13:21.801 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
art. Under $30,000 income
families, 59 percent in sports,

13:21.834 --> 13:25.738 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
still a significant percentage
but less, 41 percent in music

13:25.772 --> 13:27.774 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and art. I mean, that tells you
something. PARKER: It does. And

13:27.807 --> 13:31.310 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we also found, we asked about
after school programming for

13:31.344 --> 13:34.080 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
kids, you know, so many parents
are working now and the kids

13:34.113 --> 13:36.315 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
need somewhere to go after
school. And there was a lot of

13:36.349 --> 13:39.519 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
concern among lower income
parents about the affordability

13:39.552 --> 13:42.689 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and availability of high quality
after school programs. And we

13:42.722 --> 13:45.324 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
found that more affluent parents
are more likely to take

13:45.358 --> 13:48.361 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
advantage of those kinds of
programs. And so, with after

13:48.394 --> 13:52.331 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
school programs and also the
extracurriculars kids do on the

13:52.365 --> 13:55.101 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
weekends, and in the evening,
those things take resources. And

13:55.134 --> 13:57.937 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I think for lower income
parents, there are just other

13:57.970 --> 13:59.939 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
places where they have to put
that money. WOODRUFF: Kim

13:59.972 --> 14:02.508 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Parker, I was struck and we
cited some of this about how

14:02.542 --> 14:05.044 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
parents of these different
income levels, what they worry

14:05.078 --> 14:07.413 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about for their children. I
mean, there's a real difference

14:07.447 --> 14:11.050 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there. PARKER: Real differences.
It was quite interesting to see.

14:11.084 --> 14:13.619 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We asked about a whole range of
different things that parents

14:13.653 --> 14:16.823 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
could be concerned about. And we
found that lower income parents

14:16.856 --> 14:19.659 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have really a different set of
concerns and they tend to

14:19.692 --> 14:22.929 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
revolve around their children's
safety. So, they are more likely

14:22.962 --> 14:26.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to worry that their child might
be shot or be beat up or

14:26.499 --> 14:31.104 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
attacked or be kidnapped. And
all parents we found, the

14:31.137 --> 14:34.173 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
overall -- the biggest concern
was that the child might be

14:34.207 --> 14:38.411 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
bullied. But for more affluent
parents, the emotional

14:38.444 --> 14:40.713 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
well-being of their kids,
whether they might be bullied or

14:40.747 --> 14:43.816 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
suffer from depression or
anxiety, those things trump

14:43.850 --> 14:46.252 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
those other types of safety
concerns that lower income

14:46.285 --> 14:49.155 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
parents have. WOODRUFF:
Professor Aber at New York

14:49.188 --> 14:52.258 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
University, does this -- how
does this track with what -- you

14:52.291 --> 14:54.994 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have done a lot of research and
writing on this, how does it

14:55.027 --> 14:56.996 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
track with what you see?
LAWRENCE ABER, NEW YORK

14:57.029 --> 14:59.999 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
UNIVERSITY: Very, very well. I
think the Pew report is

15:00.032 --> 15:04.337 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
important in getting these facts
out. Over the last two decades,

15:04.370 --> 15:09.342 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we have increasingly realized
that the kinds of worries that

15:09.375 --> 15:16.215 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the report calls out for safety,
and the kinds of concerns that

15:16.249 --> 15:19.552 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
parents have of low income, that
they can't get their kids into

15:19.585 --> 15:22.121 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
extracurricular activities.
These come from a real

15:22.155 --> 15:24.557 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
environment, differences that
children and their families live

15:24.590 --> 15:26.793 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in. Parents and children in the
upper income sector, and parents

15:26.826 --> 15:30.530 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and children in the lower income
sector are living in different

15:30.563 --> 15:35.935 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
neighborhoods, different
schools. And this affects

15:35.968 --> 15:39.105 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
parents' philosophies, attitudes
and behaviors. WOODRUFF: And it

15:39.138 --> 15:42.642 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
affects -- Professor Aber, it
affects the time these parents

15:42.675 --> 15:45.678 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
can spend with their children
including at early age -- at an

15:45.711 --> 15:50.716 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
early age. ABER: It affects time
and it affects the opportunities

15:50.750 --> 15:53.419 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that children have. Parents have
two jobs, throughout their

15:53.452 --> 15:57.156 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
children's minority. One job is
to protect them from safety and

15:57.190 --> 16:00.760 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to provide kind of security and
protect them from danger and

16:00.793 --> 16:04.730 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
provide them security and safety
to go out into the world. And

16:04.764 --> 16:08.668 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the second is when they go out
into the world, to provide

16:08.701 --> 16:12.238 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
opportunities to learn and to
develop. And these are both

16:12.271 --> 16:15.141 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
things that are affected by the
neighborhoods that they're in,

16:15.174 --> 16:18.411 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as witnessed by the data that
Pew has been reporting.

16:18.444 --> 16:21.380 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: Kim Parker, what do
you see in terms of discipline

16:21.414 --> 16:25.151 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and expectations about school
performance? PARKER: We have

16:25.184 --> 16:27.420 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
found some really interesting
findings about parental

16:27.453 --> 16:30.156 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
involvement in schools. And we
found tht across the

16:30.189 --> 16:33.192 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
socioeconomic spectrum, parents
are very involved. The low

16:33.226 --> 16:37.730 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
income and high income parents
are just as likely to say that

16:37.763 --> 16:41.534 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they go to parent teacher
conferences and go to PTA

16:41.567 --> 16:44.604 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
meetings. But we also asked
whether -- you know, do you wish

16:44.637 --> 16:46.806 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you could be more involved in
your child education, and we

16:46.839 --> 16:49.175 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
found that lower income parents
are more likely than high income

16:49.208 --> 16:51.177 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
parents to say that they do wish
that they could be more

16:51.210 --> 16:53.746 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
involved. And we had another
question where we pitted two

16:53.779 --> 16:57.850 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
opinions against each other. One
was, can you ever be too

16:57.884 --> 17:00.453 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
involved in your child's
education or too much

17:00.486 --> 17:03.856 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
involvement be sometimes a bad
thing? And higher income and

17:03.890 --> 17:06.759 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
more real educated parents, a
majority of them said, you know,

17:06.792 --> 17:09.128 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
too much involvement can be a
bad thing. But for the lower

17:09.161 --> 17:11.764 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
income parents, they said you
can never be too involved.

17:11.797 --> 17:14.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: It's fascinating.
Professor Aber, what are the

17:14.734 --> 17:18.871 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
implications of this for these
children as they grow up? ABER:

17:18.905 --> 17:24.043 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Well, the kind of thing that was
just describe where parents are

17:24.076 --> 17:28.214 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
over-concerned, perhaps has to
be seen in this environmental

17:28.247 --> 17:31.951 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
context. The kind of things that
we're talking about really

17:31.984 --> 17:35.655 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
affect two kinds of things. One
is children's language and

17:35.688 --> 17:37.990 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
cognitive development, and the
second is their social and

17:38.024 --> 17:41.060 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
emotional development -- the
soft skills, the interpersonal

17:41.093 --> 17:45.665 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
skills. And these are the very
roots of inequality that we're

17:45.698 --> 17:49.669 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
seeing in this report. This is
how our nation is beginning to

17:49.702 --> 17:54.407 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pull apart. And we need to close
that so that parents' worries in

17:54.440 --> 17:58.144 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the low income neighborhoods are
reduced and the opportunities

17:58.177 --> 18:03.015 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for their kids are much, much
brighter. WOODRUFF: Kim Parker,

18:03.049 --> 18:05.751 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
quickly, what do you see in
terms of the implications for

18:05.785 --> 18:07.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
these children as they become
adults? PARKER: Well, I think

18:07.920 --> 18:10.623 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
one thing that we haven't really
touched on is the sort of the

18:10.656 --> 18:13.926 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
backdrop for this is the
changing family structure. And

18:13.960 --> 18:16.762 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the lower share of children that
are living in households with

18:16.796 --> 18:20.199 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
two married parents is at a
record low now, 62 percent. And

18:20.232 --> 18:22.601 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a rising share of children that
are living in single parent

18:22.635 --> 18:25.938 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
homes, and they are different
economic outcomes for those

18:25.972 --> 18:28.774 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
types of families. If those
trends continue, this could have

18:28.808 --> 18:31.444 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
real implications for children's
economic well-being going

18:31.477 --> 18:35.314 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
forward. WOODRUFF: Yes, a lot to
think about and a lot for

18:35.348 --> 18:39.185 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
policymakers to pay attention
to. Kim Parker with Pew Research

18:39.218 --> 18:42.054 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Center, Professor Lawrence Aber
at New York University -- thank

18:42.088 --> 18:47.093 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you both. ABER: Thank you.
(BREAK) WOODRUFF: Stay with us,

18:55.067 --> 18:58.637 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
coming up on the NEWSHOUR: The
work of two detectives raises

18:58.671 --> 19:02.641 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
questions of how police handle
rape cases, a liberal arts

19:02.675 --> 19:06.112 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
college with a focus on
innovation, and "The Force

19:06.145 --> 19:09.949 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Awakens", the business
phenomenon of the "Star Wars"

19:09.982 --> 19:13.686 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
franchise. But, first, the
latest figures from the United

19:13.719 --> 19:18.457 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Nations Refugee Agency show that
more than 800,000 refugees and

19:18.491 --> 19:23.763 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
migrants have landed in Greece
by sea during 2015. Most of them

19:23.796 --> 19:27.099 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have arrived on the island of
Lesbos, five miles from the

19:27.133 --> 19:31.237 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Turkish coast. The impact of the
crisis on the Greeks who live on

19:31.270 --> 19:34.273 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the island has been both
economic and profoundly

19:34.306 --> 19:37.410 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
emotional, as special
correspondent Malcolm Brabant

19:37.443 --> 19:40.146 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
reports. MALCOLM BRABANT, PBS
NEWSHOUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT:

19:40.179 --> 19:44.116 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
2015 has been a transformative
year to every inhabitant of

19:44.150 --> 19:47.286 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Lesbos, not least fisherman
Costas Finteris (ph). COSTAS

19:47.319 --> 19:49.288 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FINTERIS, FISHERMAN (through
translator): Up until this year,

19:49.321 --> 19:51.290 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the sea for me meant fishing.
This year, it has changed

19:51.323 --> 19:53.292 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
things. Now, it means fishing
for people. The consequences

19:53.325 --> 19:55.294 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have been a drop in my income
because when I see someone in

19:55.327 --> 20:00.332 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
